Founded in 1993 by brothers Tom and David Gardner, The Motley Fool helps millions of people attain financial freedom through our website, podcasts, books, newspaper column, radio show, and premium investing services. Investors are walking on eggshells ahead of Cal-Maine Foods (NASDAQ:CALM) earnings report next week. It's expected to give an indication of just how low the egg industry has fallen. With its stock at levels not seen in three years, the fiscal 2017 fourth-quarter financial report will determine whether shares are scrambled further. Data source: Bureau of Labor Statistics. Chart by author. But that's the average. In some regional markets like the Southeast, the industry's Urner Barry price index showed large eggs falling as low as $0.86 per dozen earlier this year. The problem, of course, is the aftereffects of the avian flu outbreak in 2015 that devastated flocks of hen layers. The influenza virus is highly contagious and can cause entire flocks to become infected very quickly. The 2014-2015 outbreak of the H5N2 virus led to the slaughter of over 40 million birds, some 12% of the national laying flock. The loss of so many birds savaged huge swaths of the country's egg inventory and prices soared. BLS data shows the average price of a dozen eggs peaked at almost $3 in September 2015, but what surprised many was how rapidly the industry bounced back. The USDA reported flock sizes were quickly repopulated to near pre-outbreak levels, but unfortunately demand did not return with it and egg prices were pummeled. An outbreak again this past spring had producers worried it would be deja vu all over again, but this time it was quickly contained. Image source: Getty Images. Still, it's a problem for Cal-Maine, the country's largest egg producer, along with other farmers. Cal-Maine admits its operating results are significantly affected by the fluctuations that go on in the wholesale shell egg market, over which it has no control. Even small increases in production or decreases in demand can have a large adverse effect on shell egg prices. The impact was evident when Cal-Maine was forced to suspend its quarterly dividend payment after recording larger-than-expected fiscal first-quarter losses last September. While the situation hasn't improved in the two years following the end of the virus outbreak, CEO Adolphus Baker is hopeful the tide will turn. Bloomberg reports he noted at an analyst conference last month that the egg industry goes through boom and bust cycles periodically, and while "high prices cure high prices" because farmers increase their flock sizes, "low prices also cure low prices" as farmers reduce them. However, it might not be so easy this time. Egg producers remain under pressure to increase their cage-free flocks, with companies like McDonald's (NYSE:MCD) pledging to go cage-free at its 16,000 restaurants within 10 years, and Taco Bell has already completed the task. And after McDonald's made its pledge, around 200 other companies followed suit, including Starbucks, PepsiCo, and Wal-Mart (NYSE:WMT). Image source: Getty Images. The move to cage-free eggs allows corporations to virtue signal how good they are, but conditions aren't really all that much better for the chickens, and consumers are still buying based on price -- leaving producers like Cal-Maine Foods caught in the middle. Wal-Mart accounts for 29% of total sales, making it all the more difficult for Cal-Maine. That's why Cal-Maine has been trying to build up its specialty egg business, which is much less volatile than the shell egg market. Where average prices of non-specialty eggs plunged almost 40% year over year last quarter, Cal-Maine's specialty egg prices were down just 5%. It says specialty eggs are now its primary growth strategy focus, and while they accounted for around 24% of its total sales volume last quarter -- the same as last year -- specialty egg revenue was 40% of total shell egg revenue compared to 31% a year ago. Don't expect Cal-Maine Foods to crow about a dramatic U-turn in its prospects in its coming earnings report. Despite the stock being down 20% so far this year, investors might not be clucking for long about its poor performance. Rich has been a Fool since 1998 and writing for the site since 2004. After 20 years of patrolling the mean streets of suburbia, he hung up his badge and gun to take up a pen full time.
